globals.name: globals
globals.description: Documentation for the various things Figura adds to the global lua state

methods.name: toJson
methods.description:
Takes any lua value, and converts it into a json string.
Does not accept functions, they will be treated as null.

methods.name: printTable
methods.description:
The first argument is either a Table, or it's a Userdata, which refers to any of the added Figura types
Prints the table out to chat, specially formatted
If userdata is passed in, it is automatically converted to a table or string, and displayed
In the case of tables inside of tables, the "maxDepth" parameter will be used to determine how far to go
Default value for maxDepth is 1
Third argument, "silent", will skip the chat print and will only return the string

methods.name: printJson
methods.description:
Takes a Minecraft JSON string as an argument, and prints it to the chat formatted, without the lua print header
Even though the syntax says only one argument, you can put as many as you want
All of them will print, and they'll be appended in the end of the previous argument
Returns the formatted string

methods.name: parseJson
methods.description:
Takes a JSON string as an argument, and converts it into a lua value.
Objects and arrays are converted to tables appropriately.

methods.name: require
methods.description:
The require() function takes the name of one of your scripts, without the .lua extension
If this script has not been already run before, it will run that script and return the value that script returns
If it has been run before, then it will not run the file again, but it will return the same thing as the first time
If a required script has no returns, then require() will return true
If the name you give isn't any of your scripts, it will error
Scripts can be accessed relative to the executing script using `./` and `../`

methods.name: print
methods.description:
A function that writes its arguments to chat
Even though the syntax says only one argument, you can put as many as you want
All of them will print, and they'll be separated by a tab space
Returns the string representation of all values

methods.name: listFiles
methods.description:
A function that returns a table with all script file names from the specified path
If no path is specified, it will fetch from the root folder
A second argument, boolean, can be given to also list files inside subfolders
Folders can be accessed relative to the executing script using `./` and `../`

methods.description:

Accessed using the name "events"

fields.name: ENTITY_INIT
fields.description: The ENTITY_INIT event is run once this avatar's entity exists

fields.name: TICK
fields.description: The TICK event is run every tick in-game if this avatar's entity exists

fields.name: WORLD_TICK
fields.description: The WORLD_TICK event is run every in-game tick

fields.name: RENDER
fields.description:
The RENDER event is run every frame, before the avatar is rendered
Takes a parameter delta, which is a number from 0 to 1 indicating the proportion of the way the game is between ticks
A second parameter, giving out context of the current RenderMode, with is a string with the name of the source of this render event
And a third paramenter, being the source matrix used to render the Avatar

fields.name: POST_RENDER
fields.description:
The POST_RENDER event runs every frame after the avatar is rendered
Takes a parameter delta, which is a number from 0 to 1 indicating the proportion of the way the game is between ticks
A second parameter, giving out context of the current RenderMode, with is a string with the name of the source of this render event
And a third parameter, being the source matrix used to render the Avatar

fields.name: WORLD_RENDER
fields.description:
The WORLD_RENDER event is run every frame before the world is rendered
Always runs when a world is visible, even when the avatar itself is not, so this runs even in first person
Takes a parameter delta, which is a number from 0 to 1 indicating the proportion of the way the game is between ticks

fields.name: POST_WORLD_RENDER
fields.description:
The POST_WORLD_RENDER event runs every frame after the world is rendered
Always runs when a world is visible, even when the avatar itself is not, so this runs even in first person
Takes a parameter delta, which is a number from 0 to 1 indicating the proportion of the way the game is between ticks

fields.name: CHAT_SEND_MESSAGE
fields.description:
The CHAT_SEND_MESSAGE event is run every time you send a message in chat
A string parameter is passed in, which contains the message that was sent
The return value is chained to the next events of the same type, whereas NIL cancels the message from being sent and any other value will modify the sent message (if allowed in the settings)

fields.name: CHAT_RECEIVE_MESSAGE
fields.description:
The CHAT_RECEIVE_MESSAGE event is run every time a message is received in chat
The first argument is the raw string of the received text
The second argument is a JSON string representation of the received text
If the first return value is not nil, the message will be replaced with that value
If the first return value is false, it will suppress adding this message
The second return value is, optionally, an RGB vector which will be used as the background color for this message

fields.name: SKULL_RENDER
fields.description:
Called on every one of your skull blocks placed in the world
It have 5 arguments, as listed below:
(number) - the tick delta
(blockstate) - the block, when rendered from a block
(itemstack) - the item, when rendered from an item
(entity) - the entity, when rendered from an entity
(string) - the type of the rendering (LEFT_HAND, HEAD, BLOCK, )
If the return value is true, the skull will not render

fields.name: MOUSE_SCROLL
fields.description:
The MOUSE_SCROLL event runs every time the mouse is scrolled
Takes a parameter delta, which is the direction of the scroll
If returned true, the event cancels its vanilla function

fields.name: MOUSE_MOVE
fields.description:
The MOUSE_MOVE event runs every time the mouse is moved around
Takes two parameters, x and y, which is the difference from the mouse position based on the latest saved position
If returned true, the event cancels its vanilla function
Note that canceling the vanilla function also cancels saving the last mouse position

fields.name: MOUSE_PRESS
fields.description:
The MOUSE_PRESS event runs every time a mouse button is pressed
Takes three number parameters, a "button", which is the number id of the button that was been pressed, the "action", which is the status of the press event (0 for release, 1 for press, 2 for hold), and the "modifier", which is a bitmask number detecting if you have any modifier keys being pressed (like shift or alt, for example)
If returned true, the event cancels its vanilla function

fields.name: KEY_PRESS
fields.description:
The KEY_PRESS event runs every time a keyboard key is pressed
Takes three number parameters, a "key", which is the number id of the key that was been pressed, the "action", which is the status of the press event (0 for release, 1 for press, 2 for hold), and the "modifier", which is a bitmask number detecting if you have any modifier keys being pressed (like shift or alt, for example)
If returned true, the event cancels its vanilla function

fields.name: CHAR_TYPED
fields.description:
The CHAR_TYPED event runs every time a character is inputted
Takes three parameters, the resulting "string" after converting the code point, the "modifier", which is a bitmask number detecting if you have any modifier keys being pressed (like shift or alt, for example), and the "codepoint" of the inputted char

fields.name: USE_ITEM
fields.description:
The USE_ITEM event is run every time the entity uses an item
The item, action and amount of particles this item would produce is given as argument
If returned true, the event cancels its vanilla function

fields.name: ARROW_RENDER
fields.description:
The ARROW_RENDER event is run for every arrow entity shot by the Avatar owner
It takes two arguments, the tick delta, and the arrow entity
Returning "true" stops this arrow from rendering, including the Arrow parent parts
Requires the "Vanilla Model Change" permission

fields.name: TRIDENT_RENDER
fields.description: figura.docs.events.trident_render

fields.name: ITEM_RENDER
fields.description:
Called on every one of your items that is being rendered
It takes six arguments: the item being rendered, the rendering mode, the position, rotation, and scale that would be applied to the item, and if it's being rendered in the left hand
Returning a ModelPart parented to Item stops the rendering of this item and will render the returned part instead

fields.name: ON_PLAY_SOUND
fields.description:
Called every time a new sound is played
Takes the following as arguments: the sound's ID, its world position, volume, pitch, if the sound should loop, the sound's category, and the sound's file path

fields.name: RESOURCE_RELOAD
fields.description: Called every time that the client resources are reloaded, allowing you to re-create or update resource texture references

You may register functions to one, and those functions will be called when the event occurs

methods.name: register

fields.name: press
fields.description:
A function that runs when the key is pressed down
The function has two arguments
The first argument is a number containing a bitmask of the currently held modifier keys
Shift = 1, Ctrl = 2, Alt = 4
The second argument is this keybind itself
If the return value is true then all vanilla keybinds using same key will be ignored

fields.name: release
fields.description:
A function that runs when the key is released
The function has two arguments
The first argument is a number containing a bitmask of the currently held modifier keys
Shift = 1, Ctrl = 2, Alt = 4
The second argument is this keybind itself
If the return value is true then all vanilla keybinds using same key will be ignored

children.name: VectorsAPI
children.description:
A global API which provides functions dedicated to creating and otherwise manipulating vectors
Accessed using the name "vectors"

methods.name: rotateAroundAxis
methods.description: Rotates a vector relative to a rotation vector

methods.name: hexToRGB
methods.description:
Parses a Hex string color into an RGB format vector
The hex "#" is optional, and it can have any length, however only the first 6 hex digits are evaluated, short hex (length 3) is also supported
For example, "#42" is the same as "420000", and "F0B" is the same as "FF00BB"

methods.name: toCameraSpace
methods.description: Converts a position in the world into a position relative to the viewer's camera

methods.name: angleToDir
methods.description: Converts a pitch/yaw angle (in degrees) into a direction vector

methods.name: worldToScreenSpace
methods.description: Converts a position in the world into a position relative to the viewer's screen

methods.name: vec2
methods.description:
Creates and returns a Vector2 with the given values
Nil values become zero

methods.name: vec3
methods.description:
Creates and returns a Vector3 with the given values
Nil values become zero

methods.name: rgbToHSV
methods.description: Converts the given color from RGB format to HSV format

methods.name: hsvToRGB
methods.description: Converts the given color from HSV format to RGB format

methods.name: rgbToHex
methods.description:
Converts the given color from RGB format to Hex format
The "#" is not included on the return value

methods.name: intToRGB
methods.description: Converts the given color from Integer format to RGB format

methods.name: rgbToInt
methods.description: Converts the given color from RGB format to Integer format

methods.name: vec4
methods.description:
Creates and returns a Vector4 with the given values
Nil values become zero

methods.name: vec
methods.description:
Creates and returns a vector of the appropriate size to hold the arguments passed in
For example; if you call vec(3, 4, 0, 2), then the function will return a Vector4 containing those values
There is a global alias "vec" for this function, meaning the "vectors." can be omitted

children.name: Vector2
children.description:
A vector that holds 2 numbers
Can be created using functions in the "vectors" api

methods.name: unpack
methods.description: Returns this vector's values as separate numbers

methods.name: clampLength
methods.description:
Modifies this vector so that its length is between minLength and maxLength
If the vector has length zero, it is unmodified
Returns self for chaining

methods.name: clamped
methods.description:
Returns a modified copy of this vector, with its length clamped from minLength to maxLength
If the vector has length zero, then the copy does too

methods.name: toRad
methods.description: Returns a copy of this vector, in radians

methods.name: applyFunc
methods.description:
Calls the given function on each element of this vector, and sets the values of the vector to the returns
The current index and its value is given as arguments of the function
Returns self for chaining

methods.name: augmented
methods.description:
Returns the augmented form of this vector
The augmented form is a Vector of the same length + 1
The new axis will have the given value, or 1 when it is not specified

methods.name: toDeg
methods.description: Returns a copy of this vector, in degrees

methods.name: lengthSquared
methods.description:
Returns the length of this vector squared
Suitable when you only care about relative lengths, because it avoids a square root

methods.name: add
methods.description: Adds the given vector or values to this one, and returns self for chaining

methods.name: length
methods.description: Returns the length of this vector

methods.name: floor
methods.description: Returns a copy of this vector with its values rounded down

methods.name: ceil
methods.description: Returns a copy of this vector with its values rounded up

methods.name: scale
methods.description: Scales this vector by the given factor, and returns self for chaining

methods.name: offset
methods.description: Offsets this vector by the given factor, adding the factor to all components, and returns self for chaining

methods.name: transform
methods.description: Transforms this vector by the given matrix, and returns self for chaining

methods.name: dot
methods.description: Returns the dot product of this vector with the other

methods.name: set
methods.description:
Sets this vector to have the given values
Nil values are treated as zero
Returns self for chaining

methods.name: copy
methods.description: Creates and returns a copy of this vector

methods.name: normalize
methods.description:
Modifies this vector so that its length is 1 unless its length was originally 0
Returns self for chaining

methods.name: reset
methods.description: Resets this vector back to being all zeroes, and returns itself for chaining

methods.name: reduce
methods.description: Reduces this vector modulo the given vector or values, and returns self for chaining

methods.name: normalized
methods.description: Returns a copy of this vector with length 1 unless its length was originally 0

methods.name: sub
methods.description: Subtracts the given vector or values from this one, and returns self for chaining

methods.name: mul
methods.description: Multiplies the given vector or values into this one, and returns self for chaining

methods.name: div
methods.description: Divides this vector by the given vector or values, and returns self for chaining

children.name: MatricesAPI
children.description:
A global API which provides functions dedicated to creating and otherwise manipulating matrices
Accessed using the name "matrices"

methods.name: yRotation3
methods.description:
Creates a new Matrix3 that rotates by the specified angle around the Y axis
Angle is given in degrees

methods.name: zRotation3
methods.description:
Creates a new Matrix3 that rotates by the specified angle around the Z axis
Angle is given in degrees

methods.name: rotation2
methods.description:
Creates a new Matrix2 that rotates by the specified angle
Angle is given in degrees

methods.name: xRotation3
methods.description:
Creates a new Matrix3 that rotates by the specified angle around the X axis
Angle is given in degrees

methods.name: rotation4
methods.description:
Creates a new Matrix4 that rotates by the specified angles
Angles are given in degrees, and the rotation order is ZYX

methods.name: mat2
methods.description:
Creates a Matrix2 using the given parameters as columns
If you call the function with no parameters, returns the 2x2 identity matrix

methods.name: mat3
methods.description:
Creates a Matrix3 using the given parameters as columns
If you call the function with no parameters, returns the 3x3 identity matrix

methods.name: mat4
methods.description:
Creates a Matrix4 using the given parameters as columns
If you call the function with no parameters, returns the 4x4 identity matrix

methods.name: rotation3

Angles are given in degrees, and the rotation order is ZYX

methods.name: scale4

fields.name: client
fields.description: The global instance of ClientAPI

children.name: ClientAPI
children.description:
A global API used to interact with the current Minecraft client
Most of its functions return things that can be found in the F3 menu

methods.name: getFPS
methods.description:
Gets the FPS of the client
Returns 0 if the fps counter isn't ready yet (or if your PC is just that bad)

methods.name: getGuiScale
methods.description:
Returns the current value of your Gui Scale setting
If you use auto, then it gets the actual current scale

methods.name: isModLoaded
methods.description: Checks if the client has loaded the given mod ID

methods.name: isPaused
methods.description: Returns true if the client is paused

methods.name: getCameraRot
methods.description: Returns the rotation of the viewer's camera

methods.name: getFOV
methods.description: Returns the current FOV option of the client, not including additional effects such as speed or sprinting

methods.name: getServerBrand
methods.description:
Returns the type of server you're on
In singleplayer, this is "Integrated"

methods.name: getClientBrand
methods.description: Returns the "version type" of your client, usually the client modloader brand

methods.name: getFPSString
methods.description:
Gets the FPS string of the client, displayed in the F3 menu
Contains info on the fps, the fps limit, vsync, cloud types, and biome blend radius

methods.name: getVersionName
methods.description: Returns the extended name of the Minecraft version of your client

methods.name: getCurrentEffect
methods.description:
Returns the path to the currently applied shader, used when spectating an entity that has different vision than normal
Normally returns nil

methods.name: getJavaVersion
methods.description: Returns your current Java version you're playing Minecraft with

methods.name: getUsedMemory
methods.description: Returns the number of bytes of memory Minecraft is currently using

methods.name: getEntityCount
methods.description: Returns the number of currently loaded entities

methods.name: getMaxMemory
methods.description: Returns the maximum amount of memory that Minecraft will try to use

methods.name: getChunkStatistics
methods.description:
Returns a string containing information about the player's chunk
This string appears in the F3 menu

methods.name: getParticleCount
methods.description: Returns the number of currently loaded particles

methods.name: getAllocatedMemory
methods.description: Returns the maximum amount of memory that Minecraft could possibly use

methods.name: getSoundStatistics
methods.description:
Returns a string containing information about the currently playing sounds on the client
This string appears in the F3 menu

methods.name: getTextWidth
methods.description:
Returns the width of the given text in pixels
In case of multiple lines, return the largest width of all lines

methods.name: getSystemTime
methods.description: Returns the current system time in milliseconds

methods.name: hasShaderPackMod
methods.description: Checks if the client has a Shader Pack mod installed

methods.name: isHudEnabled
methods.description: Returns true if the hud is enabled (F1 disables the HUD)

methods.name: getActiveLang
methods.description: Returns a string representation of the current game language

methods.name: getWindowSize
methods.description: Returns the size of the Minecraft window in pixels, as {width, height}

methods.name: getMousePos
methods.description: Returns the position of the mouse in pixels, relative to the top-left corner

methods.name: isWindowFocused
methods.description: Returns true if the Minecraft window is currently focused

methods.name: getTextDimensions
methods.description: Returns the width and height of the given text, wrapping lines and trimming to a max width

methods.name: getTextHeight
methods.description: Returns the height of the given text in pixels

methods.name: getShaderPackName
methods.description: Returns a string with the current shader pack name, empty if none is being used.

methods.name: getCameraDir
methods.description: Returns a unit vector pointing in the direction that the camera is facing

methods.name: getCameraEntity
methods.description: Returns the entity the camera is currently targeting, so returns the entity you are currently spectating, including yourself

methods.name: intUUIDToString
methods.description: Converts an int array UUID (as 4 separated arguments) into its hexadecimal string representation

methods.name: getViewer
methods.description: Returns the player entity from the running client

methods.name: compareVersions
methods.description: Compares two versions if they are less than (-1), equals (0) or greater than (1)

methods.name: getFiguraVersion
methods.description: Gets the client Figura version

methods.name: hasResource
methods.description: Checks if the specific resource exists within the client resources

methods.name: generateUUID
methods.description: Generates a random UUID

methods.name: isSnapshot
methods.description: Returns if the client is running a snapshot or full release version

methods.name: uuidToIntArray
methods.description: Converts a string UUID into its int array representation, returning a varargs of 4 ints

methods.name: hasShaderPack
methods.description: Checks if the client is currently using a Shader Pack

methods.name: getCameraPos
methods.description: Returns the position of the viewer's camera

methods.name: getFrameTime
methods.description:
Returns the current fraction between the last tick and the next tick
This is the value used as "delta" in the RENDER event

methods.name: getAtlas
methods.description:
Returns a TextureAtlasAPI object with information about the given atlas
Returns nil if the atlas was not found

methods.name: listAtlases
methods.description: Returns a list of all registered atlases paths

methods.name: getTabList
methods.description: Returns a table with the text shown in the tablist

methods.name: getServerData
methods.description: Returns a table with information on the currently connected server (also for singleplayer worlds)

methods.name: getEntityStatistics
methods.description:
Returns a string containing information about the loaded entities on the client

methods.name: entity
methods.description:
Raycasts an Entity in the world
If successful, returns the EntityAPI hit and the exact world position hit as a Vector3.
When unsuccessful, returns nil.
predicate is a function that prevents specific entities from being raycasted.
Takes in a single EntityAPI object. Return true for valid entities, false for invalid.
Marks all entities as valid when nil

methods.name: block
methods.description:
Raycasts a Block in the world.
If successful, returns the BlockState hit, the exact world position hit as a Vector3, and the side of the block that was hit.
When unsuccessful, returns nil.
blockCastType and fluidCastType determine how the raycast handles block shapes and fluids.
Will default to "COLLIDER" and "NONE" when nil

fields.name: type
fields.description:
Figura overrides lua's type() function

methods.description:
Returns the shortest angle between two angles

methods.name: lerpAngle
methods.description:
Similar to the default lerp function, but numbers are limited to the range of 0-360
Lerp is done towards the shortest angle
For example, a lerp of 340 and 20, with a factor of 0.75, will return 10

methods.name: lerp
methods.description:
Linearly interpolates from its first argument to its second argument, with the third argument as the parameter
Works on both regular numbers, vectors of the same type, and matrices of the same type

methods.name: map
methods.description:
Maps the given value from one range to another
For example, if you have a value of 20 in the range 0-200, and you want to map it to the range 100-200, the result will be 110
